result.execSummary:
The defendant Nanci L. Gavin was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Vehicle Operator Flee/Elude Officer, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.04(3).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Nanci L. Gavin in court.  Court states case and appearances.  DE is here for IH in re: to her petition for court-appointed appellate counsel.  DE states she applied at PD's office but didn't qualify.  Court questions DE on income/assets.  Court finds DE isn't eligible for court-appointed attorney as she has some cash available to her and she makes enough that she makes enough money in wages/maintenance that she would not qualify.  DE requests Court to recalculate and explains why.  Court does that and still feels she wouldn't qualify so the petition is denied.  DE requests the whole matter be undone.  Court requests clarification.  DE explains/says matter was manufactured.  Court advises judgment will stand and advises DE to seek counsel.

Defendant Nanci L. Gavin in court with attorney Cole Daniel Ruby.  Michael Albrecht and Dennis Ryan appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court states case and parties state appearances.  Atty Ruby explains his motion/wonders if the State is opposing all or part of the motion.  State says they are opposed to the entire motion.  Atty Ruby explains reasons for request of stay of sentence.  Atty Albrecht responds/against stay of sentence and DE going on trip out of the country.  Court grants request for stay of sentence of probation pending appeal.  It's continued until 9/18/2015 or if appeal isn't filed in a timely matter or decision is in before that then the stay is lifted 10 days after that.  With the staying of probation then the DE would be allowed to travel out of the country.  Court will specifically allow that travel out of the country.  Atty Ruby files a formal order for the Court's signature.  Stay is effective today.  Bond continued pending appeal.

Instruction conference.  Court proposes to go through packet provided yestereday.  #100 no objection;  #115 state objects to fleeing count verbiage - Ruby objects to removing language.  Albrecht argues.  Court rules words will be removed.  #2630 to be adjusted.  Elements #2 adjusted.  Affirmative defense - Ruby comments.  Albrecht responds.  Court believes not appropriate, no evidence to support.  Affirmative defense removed.  Mistake instruction - Ruby comments - alter somewhat.  Albrecht responds.  Court declines this instruction.  Last 2 paragraphs no objection.  4 counts of obstruction:  Elements - up to affirmative defense on 3rd page is standard.  Albrecht no objection up to elements of the crime #3.  Ruby agrees last sentence be removed.  Albrecht states concern to this section.  Requests additional verbiage.  Ruby responds.  Albrecht agrees.  Court reads.  Ruby agrees.  Albrecht responds.  Court re-reads.  Albrecht agrees.  Ruby agrees.  Court approves.  #4 no objection.  Affirmative defense as to obstruction; Ruby agrees to modify as suggested.  Albrecht objects.  Court denies, not appropriate defense.  Mistake language - Ruby same argument.  Court deletes.  Alter 1 & 2.  Court will delete alternative 2.  Burden of proof standard no objection.  #103 remove 3rd one,   #150 stricken, # 157 approved,  #160 approved,  #180 approved,  #315 & #325 removed.  Ruby comments on discovery violation; Albrecht argues.  Ruby argues.  Court affixes after #103.  Ryan remarks.  Court exercises rule and will advise.  Verdict on count 1 - change to be consistent.  Recess at 10:04.  Back on record 10:32 am.  Court on break also adjusted #1766 first 3 paragraphs.  All agree.  Jury back 10:37 am.  Court instructs jury.  State gives closing argument. Defendant Nanci L. Gavin in court with attorney Cole Daniel Ruby.  Michael X. Albrecht appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court officer Botten appears.  State calls Officer William Botten, RPD deputy - S&T.  Motion hearing on several motions.  Witness ID'd defendant.  Atty Ruby does cross-exam of Officer Botten.  State does re-direct.  Atty Ruby does re-cross.  Witness excused.  State rests.  No testimony from defense.  Court questions any other evidentiary motions to be addressed.  State doesn't believe there are any.  Atty Ruby addresses his motion/will waive argument at this time.  State does argument.  Court denies the motion to suppress the second stop and explains reasons why.  Court notes number of other motions filed to be addressed.  State notes they had no motions.  Atty Ruby notes motion filed 11/14/14 by State/other acts evidence.  Atty Ruby isn't objecting to that motion or the discovery motion.  Court declines to hear motion re: jury instruction at this time/would hear it later if necessary.  DE motion re: more definite and certain is addressed by Atty Ruby.  State responds.  Motions in limine addressed (10 total motions filed).  Motion to sequester #1 will be granted.  Voir dire and openings are not sequestered and the court officer is the exception.  #2 and 3 - everything will be recorded/reported.  #4 - enforcement of discovery.  Atty Ruby can raise this at the time if necessary.  State notes his concern re: conversation DE may have had w/the police chief.  #5 - can be raised if/when it arises.  Atty Ruby notes he hasn't filed his newest witness list yet but he will submit that.  #6 - other acts.  Atty Ruby has nothing to add.  #7 - Court will rule if necessary.  #8 - could be raised at the time of offer of evidence if one is made.  #9 - Court won't rule on this until he reviews document filed by the State this morning.  Atty Ruby notes he will be responding by brief also.  Court will take matter under advisement pending those submissions, including on #10.  Court orders any submissions be provided by Atty Ruby by 12/30/2014.  State's reply would be due by 1/8/2015.  Court is adjourned.
